{{Infobox AFL club season | club = [[St Kilda Football Club]] | season = 2008 | image = St Kilda Jumper 2002.png | imagesize = 120px | caption = St Kilda's guernsey for the 2008 season | president = [[Greg Westaway]] | coach = [[Ross Lyon]] | captain = [[Nick Riewoldt]] | home ground = [[Docklands Stadium]] | preseason comp = [[2008 NAB Cup|Preseason competition]] | preseason result = Champions | regularseason comp = [[2008 AFL season|Home and Away]] | regularseason result = 4th | finals series = [[2008 AFL finals series|Premiership]] | finals result = Preliminary finalists | club b&f = [[Trevor Barker Award|Best and Fairest]] | best and fairest = [[Sam Fisher (footballer)|Sam Fisher]] | leading goalscorer = [[Nick Riewoldt]] (65) | highest attendance = | lowest attendance = | average attendance = 40,340 (including home finals) | prevseason = [[2007 St Kilda Football Club season|2007]] | nextseason = [[2009 St Kilda Football Club season|2009]] }} [[St Kilda Football Club]] competed in the 2008 [[Australian Football League]] (AFL) season, the 150th anniversary year of the first official game of the sport now known as [[Australian rules football]].
==NAB Cup competition== The season began well with the club winning the preseason competition, the [[2008 NAB Cup]].
The club had wins over Richmond in the round of 16, Geelong in the quarter-finals, Essendon in the semi-finals and won the final against the [[Adelaide Crows]] by five points at Football Park (AAMI stadium) 2-7-9-(69) to 0-9-10-(64) - St Kilda's third preseason cup win in the AFL. Jason Gram won the Michael Tuck medal for the player judged best on ground during the final.
==Home and away rounds== [[Image:Aflgame.jpg|thumb|300px|right|St Kilda defeated Essendon (Round 22) 31/8/08 - (Click to expand)]] Despite the promising start, the Saints went on to have a mixed first half of the season with a five-win, six-loss record. After this their fortunes vastly improved and they gained a place in the finals series.
This mixed season drew both criticism and praise at differing times towards Lyon from supporters and the media. His game plan has been described as one championing accountability, similar to the [[Sydney Swans]] model by [[Paul Roos]].<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,,23892430-11088,00.html All one way for Saint Nick Dal Santo]</ref> Lyon's surprise move to drop midfielder [[Nick Dal Santo]] (as well as [[Stephen Milne]] from the side was due to them not meeting these "benchmarks".<ref>[http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/rise-and-fall-of-saint-nick/2008/06/19/1213770827314.html Rise and Fall of Saint Nick]</ref> Arguably, it was a turning point in the Saints' season, as they went on to win the next four games following this bold move.
